BHP Billiton, Pinnacle, Telkom May Be Active: South African Equity Preview

-- B y   N a s r e e n   S e r i a
-- 
2011-02-21T05:49:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-20/bhp-billiton-pinnacle-telkom-south-african-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in  South Africa .
Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names and prices
are from the last close.  South Africa’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index lost 208.88,
or 0.6 percent, to 32,514.03 in Johannesburg.    BHP Billiton Ltd . (BIL SJ): Marius Kloppers, chief
executive officer of the world’s largest mining company, said
takeovers are on his agenda even after pledging to spend $80
billion on BHP’s own projects. The shares dropped 7.36 rand, or
2.6 percent, to 276.79 rand.    Eqstra Holdings Ltd . (EQS SJ): The industrial and heavy
equipment rental company posted first-half earnings per shares
of 30.4 cents compared with a loss of 21.1 cents a year earlier.
The stock was unchanged at 6.30 rand.    Freeworld Coatings Ltd . (FWD SJ): Kansai Paint Co., Japan’s
largest paint company, said it has 90.3 percent of South
Africa’s Freeworld Coatings following its bid for the company.
Freeworld shares will continue to trade in Johannesburg. The
shares lost 79 cents, or 6.7 percent, to 11.02 rand.    Pinnacle Point Group Ltd . (PNG SJ): The property and golf-
resorts developer appointed Sibusiso Gamede, who is currently a
senior official in the Department of  Rural Development  and Land
Reform, as chief executive officer. The shares slid 50 percent
to 1 cent.  Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TKG SJ): Africa’s biggest fixed-
line operator may name Romeo Kumalo, an executive at Vodacom
Group Ltd., as chief executive officer, the Sunday Times
reported, without saying where it got the information. Pynee
Chetty, a spokesman for Telkom, said he wasn’t privy to
discussions of the company’s board, declining to comment further
when contacted by Bloomberg. The shares increased 52 cents, or
1.5 percent, to 35.30 rand.  The following stocks will begin trading without the right
to the latest dividends:  Capital Property Fund (CPL SJ), Dialogue Group (DLG SJ),
Marshall Monteagle Holding SA (MTE SJ), Redefine Properties Ltd.
(RDF SJ).  Shares or American depositary receipts of the following
South African companies closed as follows:  Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) fell 1.9 percent to $25.96.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) advanced 0.5 percent to $47.55.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BBL US) dropped 2.9 percent to $77.34. DRDGold
Ltd. (DROOY US) gained 0.4 percent to $4.62. Gold Fields Ltd.
(GFI US) increased 2.8 percent $17.29. Harmony Gold Mining Co.
(HMY US) rose 1.8 percent to $11.24. Impala Platinum Holdings
(IMPUY US) increased 1.5 percent to $30.19. Sappi Ltd. (SPP US)
fell 0.6 percent to $5.37. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) increased 0.4
percent to $51.24.  To contact the reporter on this story:
